<h2>Re: HW: The Tao, Kessler pp. 271-280. Due by sunset, 9/7</h2>

<p><b>From: </b>Shari Walton<br>
<b>Date: </b>9/7/97<br>
<b>Time: </b>5:57:01 PM<br>
<b>Remote Name: </b>206.11.1.100<br>
</p>

<h3>Comments</h3>

<p>I picked up on usefulness as a key point as well. When
referring to a bowl, it is often valuable because of what you can
do with it - its usefulness - not just the material substance of
it. In fact, it is the emptiness within the bowl that is most
useful. However, the substance must be correctly in place for its
function to work (a broken bowl will leak). Similarly, I think
the significant value in the Tao is in its usefulness (its
function), not its substance. As Kessler tells us, the Tao is not
a thing. However, the function relies upon the substance (even if
non-material) in order to provide that value. The substance of a
thing gives value to its function, which in turn gives value as
well.</p>
